\begin_layout Standard

The theory of General Relativity\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Einstein:Book}

\end_inset

 describes gravity as a consequence of the curvature of space and time (or space-time). One of the predictions of the theory is gravitational radiation from fluctuating mass-energy distributions\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{MTW}

\end_inset

. Although these ripples can, in principle, severely distort the space and time very near the radiator, far from the source one can express the effect of these waves as small perturbations to the otherwise flat space-time background. In this weak field limit the space-time metric can be approximated as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{\mu \nu} \simeq \eta_{\mu \nu} + h_{\mu \nu}, 
                  \quad \mbox{where} \quad   |h_{\mu \nu}| \ll 1
\label{eq:gmunu}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mu \nu}$
\end_inset

 is the Minkowski metric representing flat space and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu \nu}$
\end_inset

 is the perturbation to flat space due to the gravity wave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

By an adept coordinate transform\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{MTW}

\end_inset

 the gravitational wave may be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
h_{\mu \nu}(z,t) = 
\left(
\begin{matrix}
0    & 0        & 0          & 0 \\
0    & -h_{+}    &  h_{\times}     & 0 \\
0    & h_{\times}    & h_{+}     & 0 \\
0    & 0        & 0          & 0 
\end{matrix} 
\right) 
\cos{\omega \left( \frac{z}{c}- t \right)}
\label{eq:hmatrix}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the gravitational wave frequency and the two independent polarizations are 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\times}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

Measurable Effect on Free Masses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

From an observers point of view, we can ask about what the measurable effects are of gravitational waves. To answer this we set up two free masses, one located at the origin and one located a distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $x = L$
\end_inset

, from the origin. We can measure the separation between these two masses by sending a plane wave of light from the origin to bounce off of the far mass and measure the phase of the return wave. The accrued round trip phase is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Phi_{rt}(t_{rt}) = \int\limits_{0}^{t_{rt}} 2 \pi f \, dt
\label{eq:roundtripflat}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{rt}$
\end_inset

 is the time it takes for the light to make one round trip and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the frequency of the light. In the absence of radiation, we can do the integral by changing it into an integral over length. To do this we use the flat space metric, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mu \nu}$
\end_inset

, to relate space and time for light (
\begin_inset Formula $t_{rt} = 2 L/c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dt = dx / c$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In the presence of a gravitational wave, we instead use Equation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:gmunu}

\end_inset

 to calculate the space-time interval so now the round trip phase is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Phi_{rt}(t_{rt}) = 2 \frac{2 \pi f}{c} \int\limits_{0}^{L} \sqrt{|g_{xx}|} \, dx
                    \simeq 2 (1 - h_{+}/2) \frac{2 \pi L}{\lambda}
\label{eq:roundtrip}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 in the case of a 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

plus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 oriented wave with a period much longer than the round trip light travel time. Repeating this integral, but doing the integration now along the y-axis, we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{rt} \simeq 2 (1 + h_{+}/2) (2 \pi L / \lambda)$
\end_inset

. The difference in the phase shift between the two arms gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \Phi \simeq 2 h_{+} (2 \pi L / \lambda)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Interpreting the phase shifts as length measurements indicates that the apparent length of each arm is stretched and compressed as the gravity wave passes. A diagram of this is shown in Figure\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fig:CropCircles}

\end_inset

. The length shift is proportional to the original distance between the masses,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta L}{L} = \frac{1}{2} h_+
\label{eq:h}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 which is why a gravitational wave is usually said to cause a strain in space.
\end_layout

