\begin_layout Subsection

Radiation Amplitudes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Conservation of mass-energy, linear momentum, and angular momentum rule out monopole, dipole, and 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

magnetic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dipole radiation, respectively. With no conservation law to rule it out, the leading term in gravitational radiation is the oscillating quadrupole mass-energy distribution. In addition, for the wave to carry away energy from the source, the amplitude of the wave must decay as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim 1/r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

A rough estimate for the strain amplitude is
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Kip:300}

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
h &\sim \frac{G}{c^4}\frac{\ddot{Q}}{r} \\
  &\sim \frac{G}{c^4}\frac{E_{kin}^{ns}}{r} \\
  &\sim 10^{-19} \left(\frac{E_{kin}^{ns}}{M_{\astrosun} c^2}\right)
                    \left(\frac{1 \, \mbox{Mpc}}{r}\right)
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:h_estimate}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 using the estimate that the non-spherical kinetic energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{kin}^{ns}$
\end_inset

, contributing to gravitational radiation is roughly equal to the second time derivative of the quadrupole moment, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{Q}$
\end_inset

. This is a very optimistic estimate assuming a huge amount of energy is converted into gravitational waves in a neighboring galaxy. However, it indicates an upper limit to expected signal strengths.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The radiated energy (luminosity) is related to the strain by\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Landau:Fields}

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\frac{dE_{\mbox{\tiny GW}}}{dt} &= \frac{c^3 r^2}{4 \, G} 
                      (\dot{h_{+}^2} + \dot{h_{\times}^2}) \\
                   &\simeq 10^{34} \left(\frac{r}{1 \, \mbox{Mpc}}\right)^2
                                   \left(\frac{|h|}{10^{-23}}\right)^2 
                     \mbox{Watts}
\label{eq:Luminosity}
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 This estimate gives a very small measurable strain, even though the radiated energy is quite large; space-time is a very 'stiff' wave medium.
\end_layout

