\begin_layout Subsection

Binary Inspiral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

An extensively studied source of gravitational wave is the decaying orbit of two compact objects, usually referred to as a binary inspiral. In the LIGO band, these objects can be neutron stars and/or black holes (NS/NS, BH/NS, BH/BH).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The waveforms, from the NS/NS inspiral, are believed to be sufficiently well modeled that one can search for these signals using a matched filter technique\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Bruce:chisquare}

\end_inset

. The BH/BH waveforms are much more difficult to calculate\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{BCV1}

\end_inset

 and there is not as much confidence in these waveforms. Nevertheless, a matched filter search for these signals is currently being pursued as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

As the orbit of the two bodies progresses in time, the orbital period and separation decrease due to energy loss through gravitational radiation. As the orbital separation decreases, the amplitude and frequency of the signal increase until the binary separation falls below the Innermost Stable Circular Orbit (ISCO) and the two stars plunge together and merge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Reconstructing the merger of two neutron stars or two black holes is a very computationally intensive exercise and there are numerous, highly active efforts to calculate these dynamics and the associated gravitational radiation waveforms using fast supercomputers\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Jorge:Numerical}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

Rate Estimates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The recent discovery of PSR J0737-3039\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Parkes:Nature}

\end_inset

, a highly relativistic binary pulsar, increased the predicted rate of galactic NS/NS inspirals detectable by LIGO from one every few decades to one every few years\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Vicki:Rates}

\end_inset

. Previous estimates of merger rates were dominated by the parameters of the famous PSR B1913+16 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Hulse:Pulsar,Taylor:1913}

\end_inset

. This new binary (actually the first detected double pulsar system) has a 3X shorter coalescence time and a 7X smaller luminosity. These factors have radically changed the population and merger rate estimates for NS/NS binaries in the galaxy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Although, at the time of this writing, there have been 7 double neutron star systems discovered\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Taylor:1829}

\end_inset

, the detection rate estimates for LIGO are still precariously dependent on the tightest, darkest binary.
\end_layout

