\begin_layout Subsection

Ringdowns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Ringdowns}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

There are three distinct phases in the coalescence of two compact objects. In the first stage, the two objects orbit each other. The orbit slowly decays due to energy loss into gravitational radiation. At the end of the inspiral phase, the two objects plunge together. For black holes, this is the complicated merger phase which is being studied numerically with fast supercomputers 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Mergers}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

At some point after the merger, the black hole settles down to the point where it can be represented as a Kerr
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Kerr:BH}

\end_inset

 black hole undergoing quasi-normal mode (QNM) oscillations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Scott:RD}

\end_inset

. This phase is called the ringdown phase. The ringdown phase does not necessarily require a binary inspiral; any perturbed Kerr black hole will ringdown through the emission of gravitational waves. In this sense, the ringdown signal is one of the purest waveforms predicted by General Relativity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The most general stationary black hole metric is the Kerr-Newman metric
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{BHWDNS}

\end_inset

, which has only three free parameters: mass (M), spin (J), and charge (Q). Two important special cases of this metric are the Schwarzschild metric (charge = 0, spin = 0):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^2 = -\left(1 - \frac{2 \, G M}{c^2 r}\right) c^2 \, dt^2 
      + \left(1 - \frac{2 \, G M}{c^2 r}\right)^{-1} \, dr^2
      + r^2 \, d\theta^2 
      + r^2 \sin{\theta}^2 \, d\phi^2
\label{eq:Schwarz}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 and the Kerr metric (charge = 0):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
ds^2 = -\left(1 - \frac{2 M r}{\Sigma}\right) c^2 \, dt^2 
       -\frac{4 a M r \sin{\theta}^2}{\Sigma} \, dt d\phi
       + \frac{\Sigma}{\Delta} \, dr^2
       + \Sigma \, d\theta^2 
       + \left(r^2 + a^2 + \frac{2 M r a^2 \sin{\theta}^2}{\Sigma} \right) \, d\phi^2
\label{eq:Kerr}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a \equiv \frac{J}{M c}, \qquad  \Delta \equiv r^2 -\frac{2 \, G M r}{c^2} + a^2, 
\qquad \Sigma \equiv r^2 + a^2 \cos{\theta}^2  
\label{eq:subKerr}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 The theory of black hole perturbations and the associated radiation has a long history \InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{LivingReview:Ring}

\end_inset

. In 1957, Regge and Wheeler studied a perturbed Schwarzschild black hole and found that it was stable to small perturbations\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{RW:RD}

\end_inset

. In the 70s, work by Chandrasekhar, Detweiler, Zerilli,and others analyzed perturbations of Kerr black holes and the resulting gravitational waves. This work showed that gravitational radiation from the quadrupole mode has the form of an exponentially damped sinusoid\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Chandra:RD}

\end_inset

. Approximate analytical expressions for the central frequency (f) and the quality factor (Q) are given in fits made by Echeverria\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Echeverria:RD}

\end_inset

 to the numerical results of Leaver\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Leaver:RD}

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
f \simeq 32 \, \mbox{kHz} \left(\frac{M_{\astrosun}}{M}\right)
              \left[1 - 0.63 (1 - \Hat{a})^{3/10} \right]
\label{eq:RD_f}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
Q \simeq 2 (1 - \Hat{a})^{-9/20}
\label{eq:RD_Q}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 The ringdown waveform is 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Jolien:40m}

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
h_{ave}(t) = A e^{-\pi f t / Q} \cos{(2 \pi f t)}
\label{eq:RD_h}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A \simeq \frac{6 \times 10^{-21}}{\sqrt{Q (1 - 0.63 (1-\Hat{a})^{3/10})}}
         \left(\frac{\mbox{Mpc}}{r}\right) 
         \left(\frac{M}{M_{\astrosun}}\right)
         \left(\frac{\epsilon}{0.01}\right)^{1/2}
\label{eq:RD_A}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

 is the amplitude, suitably averaged over spin-axis orientations and source sky positions, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the mass of the black hole, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the fraction of the black hole's rest mass which gets converted into gravitational radiation, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hat{a} = (c/G) (J/M^2)$
\end_inset

 is the dimensionless spin parameter which goes from 0 (Schwarzschild) to 1 (extreme-Kerr). It should be noted that this dimensionless 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hat{a}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 the same as the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 used in Equations\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Kerr}

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:subKerr}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

For a 10 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\astrosun}$
\end_inset

 Schwarzschild black hole, if we take as a dynamical time the perimeter of the event horizon divided by the speed of light, we can also calculate a characteristic frequency, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{S} = (2 \pi R_{S}/c)^{-1} = c^3 / (4 \pi  G M) \simeq$
\end_inset

 1.6 kHz, which is quite close to the estimate of 1.2 kHz from Equation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:RD_f}

\end_inset

. The low Q of 2 (from Equation\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:RD_Q}

\end_inset

) tells us that almost all of the energy is released in just a couple cycles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Getting some physical intuition for the radiation from a Kerr black hole is somewhat more difficult. An interpretation from Detweiler\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Detweiler:Battelle}

\end_inset

 is that in a spinning black hole, the metric perturbation from the pulsation gets a frequency boost from the dragging of the inertial frame through which it passes. As the hole approaches the extreme-Kerr limit (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{a} \rightsquigarrow 1$
\end_inset

), the frequency of the wave as observed at infinity gets shifted up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

2.7
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 the frequency of an equivalent mass Schwarzschild black hole.
\end_layout

